<div class="courseblock main">
<p class="courseblocktitle"><strong>CHDV&#160;24599.  Historical and Contemporary Issues in U.S. Racial Health Inequality.  100 Units.</strong></p><p class="courseblockdesc">
This course explores persistent health inequality in the U.S. from the 1900s to the present day. The focus will be on racial gaps in urban health inequality with some discussion of rural communities. Readings will largely cover the research on Black and White gaps in health inequality, with the understanding that most of the issues discussed extend to health inequalities across many racial and ethnic groups. Readings cover the broad range of social determinants of health (socioeconomic status, education, access to health care, homelessness) and how these social determinants are rooted in longstanding legacies of American inequality. A major component of class assignments will be identifying emerging research and innovative policies and programs that point to promising pathways to eliminating health disparities.</p><p class="courseblockdetail">
Instructor(s): M. Keels&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Terms Offered: Autumn<br />
