<div class="courseblock main">
<p class="courseblocktitle"><strong>CHDV&#160;25220.  Constructing a Society of Human Rights:  A Psychological Framework.  100 Units.</strong></p><p class="courseblockdesc">
This course is designed to discuss the ways that cultural and social psychology contribute to understandings about human rights conceptually, and how human rights issues emerge from social dynamics. Over the course of the quarter, students will learn about theories on intergroup conflict and prejudice, how an individual's beliefs emerge from social contexts and shape their relationships with others, how obedience to authority is created and abused, and how social positioning and narratives influence conceptions of self and other. We will also discuss the relevance and impact of psychological study and data on human rights issues.</p><p class="courseblockdetail">
Equivalent Course(s): PBPL 25220, INRE 30600, HMRT 25220<br />
